    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2687690725" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14811458323495000704">Rating 4.5 <br/><br/>No better place to start my summer of Agatha Christie than the first in the Hercule Poirot series. A buddy read that Dana was up for and we just needed to determine which audio narration to go with. I did not realize how many different narrations there are for a single Christie book. I&apos;m a big fan of Richard Armitage and that&apos;s what we went with and it was a great choice.<br/><br/>The Mysterious Affair at Styles tells the story of the murder of Emily Ingelthorp at the household at Styles Court.</span>
  <span id="freeText14811458323495000704" style="display:none">Rating 4.5 <br /><br />No better place to start my summer of Agatha Christie than the first in the Hercule Poirot series. A buddy read that Dana was up for and we just needed to determine which audio narration to go with. I did not realize how many different narrations there are for a single Christie book. I'm a big fan of Richard Armitage and that's what we went with and it was a great choice.<br /><br />The Mysterious Affair at Styles tells the story of the murder of Emily Ingelthorp at the household at Styles Court. Arthur Hastings is a soldier is on leave and looking for a place to go when he runs into an old chum John Cavendish who invites him to Styles. John is Emily's stepson who lives there with a cast of characters including Emily's new husband Alfred. A few days after his arrival he runs into none other than the quirky Hercule Poirot who is staying down the road via Emily's hospitality. When Emily is murdered due to an apparent poisoning, Hasting runs for Poirot who methodically investigates this crime. <br /><br />Such a fun story! The Christie trademark of a cast of characters, but I found it very easy to keep track of. Hastings is such a fun character, a bit of a dolt who misses the most obvious things but works so well with Poirot. The two work together on this case...well, I think Poirot enjoys Hastings company but does not consider him to be an equal investigator. I'm happy to see he appears as his "side-kick" for a few more books. The narration was awesome, we both really enjoyed it. A great buddy read that kept us both guessing on the murders. I'll just admit....I'll never get it right in a Christie book but I love the journey!</span>
  <a data-text-id="14811458323495000704" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


